{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611009"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:06:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:06:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16194"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16194"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.93,0,0,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8885"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74608"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8885"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16194"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60102"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7607"},{"type":"tags","id":"10124"},{"type":"tags","id":"10602"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21150"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21153"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74608"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to her GP with a six-month history of amenorrhoea. She is a professional marathon runner who trains intensively for four hours daily. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with normal vital signs. Her BMI is 19 kg/m2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThyroid function tests - normal\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPregnancy test - negative\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EProlactin - 15 \u00b5g/L (4-23)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following hypothalamic hormones is most likely to be suppressed?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acetylcholine","Gonadotropin-releasing hormone","Dopamine","Serotonin","Oxytocin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents functional hypothalamic amenorrhoea secondary to intensive exercise, which leads to suppression of the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis. The key pathophysiological mechanism involves inhibition of \u003Cstrong\u003Egonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH)\u003C/strong\u003E neurons in the arcuate nucleus and preoptic area of the hypothalamus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetylcholine\u003C/strong\u003E is a neurotransmitter primarily involved in autonomic and neuromuscular function, not directly in reproductive regulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDopamine\u003C/strong\u003E acts as a prolactin-inhibiting factor in the hypothalamus. While it plays a role in reproductive function, the normal prolactin levels in this case suggest dopamine signalling is intact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerotonin\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in mood regulation and can influence GnRH secretion, but it is not the primary hormone suppressed in exercise-induced amenorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxytocin\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in labour, lactation, and social bonding, but is not directly involved in regulating the menstrual cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe suppression of GnRH leads to decreased luteinising hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) secretion from the anterior pituitary, resulting in reduced ovarian stimulation and ultimately amenorrhoea. This adaptive response can occur in situations of physical stress (such as intensive exercise), psychological stress, or low body weight.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Stress-induced suppression of the reproductive axis occurs via inhibition of GnRH neurons in the hypothalamus","The arcuate nucleus and preoptic area contain GnRH neurons that regulate the reproductive cycle","Inhibition of GnRH leads to decreased gonadotropin secretion and suppression of ovarian function"],"references":["Hawkins SM, Matzuk MM. The menstrual cycle: basic biology. Ann N Y Acad Sci. 2008;1135:10-8. doi: 10.1196/annals.1429.018. PMID: 18574203; PMCID: PMC2913133.","Tsutsumi R, Webster NJ. GnRH pulsatility, the pituitary response and reproductive dysfunction. Endocr J. 2009;56(6):729-37. doi: 10.1507/endocrj.k09e-185. Epub 2009 Jul 17. PMID: 19609045; PMCID: PMC4307809.","Barbieri RL. The endocrinology of the menstrual cycle. Methods Mol Biol. 2014;1154:145-69. doi: 10.1007/978-1-4939-0659-8_7. PMID: 24782009.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60102"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16194"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60102"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T19:48:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T19:50:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8885"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74608"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co